observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the LCE:
Require the HR to assess the existing Organizational Structure, expedite filling up of vacant positions through advertisement and assessment of qualified employees for promotion, and submit a report thereon to the LCE for approval;
Make a written policy/guidelines to address the issue on the necessity and propriety of hiring COS/JO workers, who should not perform tasks assigned to existing permanent and regular employees per their job descriptions;
Limit the hiring/deployment to those offices that are extremely in need of their services; and
Incorporate in the COS/JO contract the number of man hours, quantity and duration of the work to be performed by COS/JO personnel and require them to submit quantified accomplishment reports and signed copies of contracts to support payment of wages.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendation that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) require:

 The Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects; 

 The Municipal Accountant to include the necessary disclosure on the total road network system of the LGU in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendation that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) require:

 The Acting General Services Officer to maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map and keep a complete LRNPCs for all roads and its components;

 The Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects; 

 The Municipal Accountant to keep and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network and reconcile the same with the LRNPCs and the result of the physical inventory taking at the end of each year; and
 The Municipal Accountant to include the necessary disclosure on the total road network system of the LGU in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

We recommended that Management:

 Require the concerned Accountable Officer to submit the accounts and financial reports to the Municipal Treasurer pursuant to the timeliness of the abovementioned existing law, rules and regulations; 

 Direct the Municipal Treasurer to submit to the Municipal Accounting Office all the disbursements vouchers, payrolls, official receipts, including the corresponding reports for each month on or before the fifth day of the ensuing month or pursuant to the abovementioned pertinent provisions of rules and regulations, as applicable; 

 Direct the Municipal Accountant to strictly comply with the timeliness on the recording and submission of accounts to the Auditor within ten days of the ensuing month; and

 Identify and address the cause/s for the poor performance in the submission of monthly financial reports/accounts.

We recommended that Management:

 optimize the utilization of the 20% LDF and implement the PAPs within the timelines in order to achieve the socio-economic and environmental outcomes, essential in the attainment of its goals and objectives of a desired quality of life for its constituents;
 consider the equitable distribution on PAPs  listed among the three important aspects of Sector development mandated under DILG/DBM JMC No. 2017-1 dated February 22, 2017  and previous issuances as well as the requirements of Sections 16 and 17 of the LGC of 1991,in order to cater not only to the infrastructure needs of the constituents but also on environment, agriculture, fishery and livelihood programs, projects and activities which will directly address the actual needs of the intended beneficiaries;

 adopt a well-defined strategy in order to enhance the present monitoring and review activities during the planning, procurement, contract implementation and program evaluation phase, in order for the planners, implementers as well as evaluators to continuously monitor the timely implementation, so that immediate appropriate and corrective actions could be done on noted gaps along the way.

We recommended Management to:

 Send demand letters to concerned officials and employees with unliquidated cash advances requesting immediate settlement thereof;

 In case of failure to settle the cash advances after two demand letters, withhold the payment of salaries of the concerned accountable officers to enforce settlement thereof; 

 Before processing a claim for cash advance, the Municipal Accountant shall ensure that the previous cash advance of the concerned official or employee has been settled;
 Further he shall strictly monitor that all cash advances granted are liquidated within the required period of settlement.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:

 to conduct risk assessment;

 to identify critical processes and functions; 

 to determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation; 

 to conduct risk analysis and impact analysis; 

 to formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed template and be guided by the PSCP guidebook; and

 to submit plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.

 Further, we recommended that members of the working group be capacitated by allowing them to attend seminars/trainings on the formulation of the PSCP.

We recommended and the:
(a) Management agreed to use the remaining unspent LGSF-AM fund by fully implementing the already identified projects which are expected to help the agency improve its delivery of basic services to its constituents;
(b) Municipal Engineer, in coordination with the Municipal Planning and Development Office (MPDO), agreed to observe the timeline of project completion and strictly monitor or supervise the implementation of project activities to avoid the incurrence of delays;
(c) Municipal Engineer agreed to inform the Municipal Accountant of liquidated damages due from defaulting contractor and ensure that the amount is collected;
(d) Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the Bids and Awards Committee to strictly adhere to the above-cited provision of R.A. No. 9184 and its RIRR in the procurement activities;
(e) Municipal Accountant agreed to review thoroughly all claims presented for payment prior to approval to ensure that only properly and completely documented transactions/disbursements shall be paid; and
(f) concerned Municipal officials and personnel agreed to submit the lacking document to the Audit Team for evaluation and examination and observe stringent compliance on the submission of documentary requirements of transactions.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to instruct the EXECOM and TWG to:
(a) comply with the provision of the JMC with respect to constitution of GFPS in accordance with Item 4.1.A.2 of the said law;
(b) consider utilizing all available resources to update the GAD database;
(c) continue the monitoring of GAD PPAs and coordination with respective offices for the implementation of GAD Plan in order to fully utilize the fund intended for gender and development; and
(d) submit copy of Annual GAD Plan and Budget and GAD Accomplishment Report to the COA Audit Team within the prescribed deadline.
